SSH Setup for PowerShell (Windows):

markdown

---
title: SSH Setup for GitHub on PowerShell (Windows)
---

# SSH Setup for GitHub on PowerShell (Windows)

## 1. Check for Existing SSH Keys

```powershell
Get-ChildItem -Path ~/.ssh/

2. Generate a New SSH Key

powershell

ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"

3. Add the SSH Key to the ssh-agent

powershell

Start-Service -Name ssh-agent
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519

4. Add the SSH Key to Your GitHub Account

powershell

Get-Content ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub | clip

5. Test the SSH Key

powershell

ssh -T git@github.com

6. Use SSH URLs for Git Repositories

Finally, when you're cloning Git repositories (like the course repository), use the SSH URL: git@github.com:username/repo.git

yaml


**SSH Setup for Debian / Fedora Linux:**

```markdown
---
title: SSH Setup for GitHub on Debian / Fedora Linux
---

# SSH Setup for GitHub on Debian / Fedora Linux

## 1. Check for Existing SSH Keys

```bash
ls -al ~/.ssh

2. Generate a New SSH Key

bash

ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"

3. Add the SSH Key to the ssh-agent

bash

eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519

4. Add the SSH Key to Your GitHub Account

bash

xclip -selection clipboard < ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub

5. Test the SSH Key

bash

ssh -T git@github.com

6. Use SSH URLs for Git Repositories

Finally, when you're cloning Git repositories (like the course repository), use the SSH URL: git@github.com:username/repo.git

yaml


